column94: Well, there are obvious legal issues in violating the terms of service. Our legal department wouldn't be too happy about that and doing so would violate a host of institutional policies.  So we are back to the public data issue again. Of course there are ethical issues. And none of this is new. The Internet, cheap storage and computing power just makes it all so much easier. But it's just a playing out of practices that are hundreds of years old. Foucault was lecturing on this decades ago. See Security, Territory, Population, particularly chapter 3. For a more recent take see Bernard Harcourt.   All human knowledge has ethical concerns because none of it is separate from the exercise of power. And in the big scheme of things worrying about what IRBs do and don't know in the context of what's happening now is a bit like fiddling while Rome burns.
column112: People share all sorts of information in public without understanding how that information can be used in negative ways or has a harmful impact. An example, here would be the research (at MIT?) done years ago that showed that an analysis of public on-line behavior could be used to identify people who were gay.  That had potentially very harmful impact on people who are not 'out', at a very minimum it's an invasion of privacy by taking away their control over information about themselves.   FYI: I find the detail of these projects to minimal to answer some of the questions with certainty. I answered more oversight above but there's really not enough detail and context.
column163: It clearly doesn’t involve researcher interaction with the people about whom the data is being collected. So then the issue as to whether it involves human subjects comes down to whether it involves private identifiable information. The information is private. Is it identifiable? Practically all data has the potential for being re-identified so there has to be some judgment or standard. And that judgment would be stricter if the risk was higher. Presumably there would also be some sort of data sharing agreement involved to protect the data from use for purposes other than the stated research purposes.
column166: We have projects that fall outside the purview of IRB review all the time (e.g. because the activities don't meet the regulatory definition of research) that raise ethical issues. We have institutional policies in place to address those concerns.  In the study described above "group mobility patterns" raises the question which groups? And if the groups are minority or historically discriminated groups what are the group risks associated with the research?
column184: There's not enough information to make a judgment. We're not told the purpose. Whether it is research or not depends on the purpose. Is the purpose generalizable knowledge or is it to improve the university public health program to reduce suicide risks? One's research that might be subject to full board review and ones not research. Are we supposed to just assume it is research because we are told it is research?  From my perspective here is an activity that could be near identical but because the purpose is different one is subject to IRB review and one is not. The ethical issues don't go away merely because it isn't research.
column202: See response to previous question.  Again there's not enough information and context to make a judgment.

column112: Again, the example says data is public. So you might say our regs "fail" us, or you might say the IRB's role ends right where it should. Maybe in this new internet age, the IRB should review research on "public" information based on such factors as sensitivity of data - but then who says whether it's sensitive? The subject already posted it in public, so you might say it can't be that sensitive to them! This societal expectations online aren't worked out yet. So I would say there are a ton of ethical issues about analyzing people's drug use and tracking their behavior without them knowing. Not collecting identifiers is helpful, but we wouldn't ask since not human subjects research.
column130: From the description, we don't know how third party information is treated. An IRB might approve a waiver if the researcher successfully argues that their consent is not practicable to obtain and subjects rights and welfare are not adversely affected, but this doesn't mean there's no issue with researchers "spying" on unsuspecting users. I'm sure other concerns would come up in review, but that's what comes to mind.
column184: Well maybe this falls inside the IRB's purview, but I would just be concerned about the kind of data this would produce. Of course predicting which students might suffer mental health conditions in the future could be powerful in prevention or treatment, but it could also stigmatize people and open them up to being denied services...this sounds important and also messy.
column202: There's the ongoing debate over whether posting something to the internet should mean that now anyone should be able to use it for anything they want. I think we commonly argue that public means fair game. But this could be context-dependent. Not even telling people that their data was used means they have no chance to explain themselves.
column220: This is a good example of where the IRB regs do not cover all ethically sticky situations. If no interaction or intervention, the regs would not apply, at least so long as we agree the data is "public", which it appears to be. I would say the data is public, personally. And I'm not in favor of mission creep when it comes to the IRB. I wouldn't want to set a precedent by requiring IRB review of something that doesn't meet the HSR definition. That said, as with the last example, predicting mental health conditions is dangerous business. And only moreso when the subjects don't even know they're being studied/monitored. Very messy. And based on this description, I would still say not human subjects research.
column253: Whether data is secondary or generated for research purposes.
column256: Probably. I don't know enough about AppleHealthKit. Based on context, I'm guessing people commonly share their health data publicly online? I responded to these questions assuming this was private information, but if public, it might not be human subjects research at all, and then any ethical concern would fall outside of the IRB's purview.
column274: I would not say that all data on Facebook is necessarily public. But this example specifically says researchers are gathering public data. Therefore, I would have to say no review is required. That said, the ethics of studying people in secret is questionable (not that it's not  being done all the time). I think it attenuates risks that the researchers are only looking at group dynamics, but individual data is nonetheless collected and analyzed.
